This is a short Los Angeles Film Festival update (Full update coming soon!)

Two nights ago I was walking back to my car at around 1:30am and I saw the haggard, and eternally tired Producer of a film that is in the narrative competition, he was at the ATM, and he had that look that is so familiar to all of us: "Do I really want to accept the $2.50 service charge?!!"

Tonight he finds out that his film wins $50,000 dollars.

Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Happiness,

Marcus
This is what I am going to look like... In 30 years... in 65 years

I can't consentrate, I pretty sure that I am staring, and my sunglasses aren't dark enough. I think I might going to hell, due to impure thoughts, but Jesus Christ! 

feeling a little crazy,

Marcus

I watched the last 20 minutes of Rocky I, on Spike TV, this morning. 

Marcus
So I was on the boat yesterday talking with my father, and we both decided that you're only in your early twenties once. This is very exciting. Marcus

A Personal version of: Really?!?
By Marcus Grewe

Directions:

Really?    A questioning really, sort of just a, "That doesn't really 
                  make sense."
Really?!           More of an, you're an idiot, with lots of sarcasm
Really?!?       This is the big one, it's a "you gotta be fucking kidding
                  me!" - really. 
Huh?           This is to be read as, "I just gained 15 pounds? huh?,
                   that's weird."
Really          This just means really, like, for real. As in, the truth.

My First Act of Unemployment: A Car Accident; Really.

Here I stand, a man , a shell of a man, impenetrable, invincible, unemployed with a strained neck, actually, no, that's a lie, I'm sitting down, who types standing up? 

A CAR ACCIDENT? Really (God, Are you there it's me Marcus?) I just stopped working today, and I'm in a car accident? Really?! Oh and the guy who started the - four car pile up! - was drunk...Really!?! The last time I was in a car accident, two months ago, Really?  Really... god? a car accident? well that's good, welcome to the real world, huh? 

[3:23 am, tired Marcus passes out] 

[10:13 Marcus wakes up, calls mom, begins writing again] 

I guess I'm alive though so that's cool, really. To be honest if I had the choice between being alive or dead I would choose alive, if only because of girls and their dresses (it's called a call back people). 

When I was graduating high school, I remember people telling me to follow my dreams, a quick scene...

FADE IN:

EXT. GRADUATION - DAY

MARCUS (18) White button up shirt, pleated khakis, and green gown. Marcus is talking with his High School English teacher, MR. POWELL.

                                       MR. POWELL
                               Follow your dreams Marcus
FADE OUT.

See what I mean? Follow your dreams they said, little did I know (little did he know...) that it was all a lie, or at least a lie everyone tells themselves when they are trying to say something to a young man going through what is supposed to be a meaningful rite of passage. My problem was I actually did follow my dream, 2500 miles I followed, really. Now I live in the Valley, I have a smelly fat guy sleeping on my couch, huh? 

"But Marcus doesn't he have a wife?" Yes he does, really.
"And a child?" Yes, that too, really? 
"But he has been living in and sleeping on the couch in your apartment since January?" Yes...Tah dah! Really. 

I don't have a job anymore, my neck hurts more than it did last night, lately, no one has been laughing  at my jokes, and just so that you know exactly where I'm coming from, to really put it into perspective, I haven't been romantic with a woman in 3 non-fucking months, really. Really?Really?! Really?!?. A tear.

So don't follow your dreams children, stay near home, you'll get free food, mom will do your laundry, drinks at the bar will be cheaper, you don't have to deal with the pressure of always trying to be creative, and you won't be living in a city where four car pile-ups are a everyday occurrence amongst your 10 million neighbors. 

Really?

No, not really. I love it here, it's sunny, the women are beautiful, and I'm gonna be kicking some serious ass in the next six months. 

Just because I rock doesn't mean my heart's made of stone,

Marcus

Fuck.

So that really didn't go as well as I had hoped.

I went to see Spiderman 3 tonight against everyone in Hollywood's (save for those that are in some way connected to Columbia Pictures, that's everyone, I know, it's a paradox) wishes, and as predicted, it was bad. Not as horrible as others may think, but you know, just bad.

However...

Elizabeth Banks, who had an extremely small role, stole (in my opinion) the show. This girl is hilarious and adorable. Albeit, she may have been channeling Parker Posey, her performance was so spot-on, flawless, that I am certain P.P. couldn't have done a better job herself. Watch out for next year's model, this one is going to be a star.

Also, she was in The 40-year-old Virgin, and had the best (delivered) line of the entire film:


Hahaha-hey-ho!


Marcus

Playboy TV is looking for 3 male friends 18-25 who would like to host four hot Playboy babes chicken-fighting in a pool. Must be comfortable being seen on TV with nude female models and must know how to swim. The shoot is Wednesday, May 9th. Four hours work, $100 for each guy. We will provide transportation to location. 




Thank god they are providing transportation, because if I had to drive myself, I'd be like, "Fuck that shit! ain't nobody takin' advantage of Marcus Grewe, Homie don't play dat!!"


I just realized I don't have any male friends aged 18-25. It's hard to believe that out of all of the reasons not to do this, that would be the deal-breaker.

My two friends Chelsea and Adam are getting married this summer, and my bester friend Lindsey is throwing a bridal shower, and she is making customized fortune cookies. She wants me to help write the fortunes, here is what I have so far, please post any ideas you may have.

"It won't last"

"Two months tops"
And

"He's cheating on you"

but that probably won't go over that well, so:

"You will be attending a wedding sometime in the next three months." 

"Marriage is punishment for shoplifting in some countries"

"If you blow chunks and she comes back, she's yours. But if you spew and she
bolts, then it was never meant to be. "

"Well here you are, there it is, THIS is what it's all about."

"Help! I have been enslaved by the fortune cookie factory"

"Duck!"

"Love is all you need, and money...and sometimes ice cream is good."

"Has anyone considered the fact that Adam is, like, a lot bigger than Chelsea?"

"True love lasts forever, or at least until someone starts to gain weight"

"10 bucks says they end up with a white picket fence, any takers?"

"I bet she will hyphenate, I would"

"Sometimes the captain of the football team becomes a lawyer and marries the
head cheerleader, makes you sick doesn't it?"

"Their love will move mountains, and change diapers."

"Don't say anything, but...she's showing"

She looked way better, but still a lot like Ally Sheedy, post make-over in The Breakfast Club.

Goddammit, it is so tragic when you see, make eye contact, have a moment of understanding with, and walk away from people like that.  

idealistically,

Marcus

I don't care who you are, who your father is, even if you are my father...If you drive any model of a Hummer, I DON'T LIKE YOU. Not even a little bit. No exceptions.

Marcus

A Children's book, entitled:

"The boy who never ever, ever, ever got what he wanted out of any aspect of his life be it personal, or career, not even once just for a little bit."

Theme of the book: There isn't anything to get excited about.

Gun control? Come on, really? What's the point? do we really need gun control? What a stupid, stupid idea. Silly liberals.

Marcus 

Walther .22-caliber semi-automatic and a 9 mm Glock...you know, for hunting.

For instance:

Today is the first time I actually ran five blocks to make sure I could beat the 5 o'clock FedEx pick up, so that my Executive Producer could get a "very important" package out on time. I can't fucking wait to tell these stories when I'm all successful and shit. It'll be ten blocks though, or more, and I saved an old lady from getting hit by a car too, but trust me the package will always make it just in time.

Why did I trip and run into the wall?

Because I was staring at a pretty girl that walking towards me.

(goddamn you skirts!)

It's not porn, it's better. I'm still not sure if this makes me really happy, or really sad. Girls, please do not follow this link as it may lessen your already crumbling opinion of me.

I just want to let everyone (all five of you) know that if you don't have anything better to do* the first episode of Work Out Season Two starts tomorrow on Bravo.

*All things that are probably better to do: reading a book, surfing the internet, brushing your teeth, clipping your toenails, drinking alone, going for a run, tracing your hand and making a thanksgiving turkey for next November, taking a bath, getting a hair cut, counting to a thousand-twice, dribbling a basketball for an hour, jumping jacks, playing jacks, ironing all of your pants and shirts, sleeping, lying awake in your bed, making snow-angels (if applicable), eating ice cream, pacing, learning how to tie ship-knots, Picking out random words from the dictionary memorizing their definition and using them in three or more sentences, snorkeling...in fact the only thing that isn't better than watching Work Out is watching Top Design the other show I worked on.

I just stumbled upon a very interesting fact. I was sitting at my desk checking and re-checking my top-five websites looking for some sliver of scintillation, and when I tried to quit the inter web  would not close. I tried to force quit, didn't work, tried to restart, didn't work and then I looked at the escape button, "ha, yeah right!" eventually the force quit powered through, and I was able to go about my business. 

Then I got to thinking about the escape button. When I was younger I used the escape button all the time, but now I never use it. So I tried. I opened and ran every program on my computer, and tried to use the escape key, AND IT DID NOTHING. The escape key is obsolete; it is the most futile key out of 109 keys (hand counted!). I thought that it might have something to do with my computer being a Mac. So, I went to the accountants office (Ah Dell, looks like one of the model ships from the original Star Wars), and asked her if she ever uses escape, "No," so we opened her programs and tried to use the escape button, and that didn't do anything either. 

How did we miss this? When I was just a tike, playing Oregon Trail during "inside recess," I couldn't even see the letters on the escape button it was used so often, and now 10 years later it has become the fat boring kid in class (Sizist!!) hanging out in the corner with no one to interface with. 

Well I am flabbergasted, I have been walking around the office, mumbling to myself, "There's no escape, it was here now its gone, it does nothing, my stomach hurts, etc." Everyone is looking at me in that odd, "Dude, it's really not that big of a deal," type of way. So I guess I should let it go, and move on. I just had to get this out of my system, There may not be an escape anymore, but now I can at least quit (thinking about it).

I hate "working" on my resume. I probably hate it because I am not creative enough to make up justified explanations of what I have done in jobs past.

Office Production Assistant, Stone and Company: My duties included... Getting to work a half hour early, and making sure the coffee was made. Then I would wait around for about forty-five minutes for our receptionist to get in so that I would have someone to talk to about what I did the night before. Then I would go into my "office" (small room with computer and a dub rack), and look online for other jobs. When 12:30 would role around I would get everyone lunch, and then go back to the office, read blogs, update my myspace page, and write emails to old friends. Then around 3:30 I would go into the Executive Producer's Assistant's office, and we would talk about The O.C., old movies, and TV Shows that we liked when we were younger. Then I would go home.

Talent Production Assistant, Top Design: Stood around on set, and took cast members to the bathroom. This had the added bonus of broadcasting on the Walkie Production Channel that, "Cast member is on deck, and heading towards the bathroom," and then, "Cast member is on deck, heading back from Bathroom." Glamorous.

Clearance Coordinator, Work Out: Taking releases from someone who is on set actually getting releases. File, and enter release information into an excel workbook that no one sees other than myself, and make episode release binders that no one checks. After that invigorating two hours of work, I spend the rest of my day on ichat, or writing long arduous posts on livejournal that my friends only read because they know I will ask about it later.

I think the problem with "The Business" is that there is absolutely no job training, which means that we all need to know exactly what we are doing the moment we start on a new job, and since that is impossible, everyone has to work for two years in lame ass Production Assistant-ish jobs. This is why every employer wants at least two years of experience, which no one actually has, and we all end up in a fancy new job learning the ins and outs of said job on the fly. In the mean time we just wasted two years of our life with mindless phone answering, and coffee getting. Harrumph.

Whenever I decide to finally write my "Young Man Trying to Make it in Hollywood" novel, I am definitely going to add the night I witnessed cops show up at my neighbors apartment for domestic abuse. Everyone in the building could hear them, and since their bedroom wall is right next to mine I   got the brunt of it.

Oh, and by "the night" I mean last night. Let's hear it for making it through the hard times!

Marcus

Do you ever wonder at what point you just got to say fuck it man like when you gotta stop living up here and start living down here?

So I am sitting at the bar and this drunk man (extra?), sits down next to me and mumbles, "How's it going Marcus?" I say, "What?" and he doesn't reply. Then the Bartender (featured Extra?!), gave me this weird look, and said, "What can I get you hun?" What can I get you hun, hmmm, that's interesting? she heard this man call me Marcus, she has my credit card, and knows that my name is Marcus, but since her drunkin co-worker ( I mean co-worker in the production of "the movie of my life," not at the bar) slipped up she tries to act all like she didn't know my name even though in the world of the story she is supposed to. So, don't make a joke of this or try to explain it otherwise, because I know that you will just be doing so to try and reverse my thinking on this situation. Plus, even if  you did, I wouldn't listen anyway, because at this point I am not even sure if you really are my friends, or...my sister.

To dream that you are in a movie theater indicates that you are attempting to protect yourself from your emotions and/or actions. Viewing them on a movie screen projects them onto another person and thus makes those feelings/actions distant. You may be protecting yourself from experiencing them.

To see slow, difficult movement, indicates a fear of failure. Something is holding you back and preventing you to take chances.

To dream that you are waking up in your dream indicates that something is missing or lacking in your life. There is an aspect of your life that you are not utilizing to its fullest potential. You are not recognizing your abilities.

http://www.dreammoods.com/dreamdictionary/

I had the worst night. It took me two hours to get to sleep it usually takes 5 minutes. I think I had a bad piece of meat or something, I usually cut off all the fat but sometimes I miss. I also watched Alphaville last night, and I am fairly certain that had something to do with it. It took me so long to get to sleep because I had one of those "slip in and out of sleep" dreams, where you can't move!

The Dream:

I am inside what looks like either a movie theater or a large private screening room, and it is pitch black. My eyes will not adjust and I can't find a light switch. I am also moving in slow motion, no matter how hard I try I just can't move, it is like something or someone is holding me down. 

Then I wake up, but not the eyes opening slightly wake up, the "snap into a Slim Jim!" wake up. The kind where you feel like you are ready to kung fu the person you assume is standing over your bed with a knife. Then I look at the clock, only fifteen minutes have passed, and I seriously (and I mean seriously) cannot move at all. My muscles hurt, I want so badly to get up, and then I drift back into the dream. 

People are grabbing at me trying to get me to sit down in one of the theater seats, apparently they want me to watch, either that or I am in the way. I just want to get out, but I can't fucking move. 

Then I wake up again, and the same thing that happened the last time I woke up happens again, and this cycle repeats for two hours. 

I finally wake up at 2:30 am, I can move and I literally (figuratively) run out of my room. I am completely out of it and decide that what I really need, what can really cure my restlessness is Jack In The Box. After an Ultimate Bacon Cheeseburger Meal (#7 so nice), I fall right to sleep and dream of waterfalls, rainbows, and children of all races holding hands. Thanks Jack, you are my only friend.

In closing, I know that the risk you take when telling a dream story is that you invariably will end up having to listen to everyone else's dreams, but in this case I do not mind, so tell away.

You are officially a "water cooler" TV Show. I was in the kitchen today getting water for the coffee, my co-worker was toasting a bagel, and we were talking about "The Office." Someone who doesn't even work on the same show as us came in and joined the conversation, well, not so much a conversation, but rather a string of lines from last nights episode followed with laughter. After we had gone through every funny line we could remember, there was an awkward moment, and we all went back to work. Next week we are considering a fashion show, a fashion show, a fashion show at lunch.
